There seems to be a bug in the monogame content processors that results in the Monogame Content processors not loading.  Forums suggest that it is because you need Windows Phone SDK 7.1.  After an entire day of hunting the cause, I was able to isolate the problem down to 2MGFX.  In MojoShader.cs the crash happens on every single Struct that has the explicit layout attribute.  Basically none of the unions are loading.  I replaced them all with Sequential lay outs and took out the unions, and everything works.  I am able to load and process content w just standard XNA 4.0 Refresh installed.  

I suspect that the 7.1 sdk is working by co-incidence since it the alignment must change.  Or the 7.1 ContentProcessor doesn't load every class type, or perhaps it uses meta data to determine which types need to be loaded and ignoring the rest...

If you wish to test it yourself, try loading the Monogame Content Processor DLL from a normal app ( A standard WPF app / Win forms)

``` C#
Assembly a = null;
try
{
  a = Assembly.LoadFile(@"MonoGame\MonoGame.ContentPipeline\ContentProcessors\bin\Debug\MonoGameContentProcessors.dll");
}
```

Just loading the DLL works fine...
However as soon as you try to load the types ( which is what XNA will do to try to find all the types that are [ContentProcessors]:

``` c#
Type[] t = a.GetTypes();
```

That will throw an exception:

``` c#
if (ex is System.Reflection.ReflectionTypeLoadException)
{
   var typeLoadException = ex as ReflectionTypeLoadException;
   var loaderExceptions = typeLoadException.LoaderExceptions;
}
```

The error appears on every struct that has a union as:
System.TypeLoadException: Could not load type 'MOJOSHADER_astDataType' from assembly 'Pipeline, Version=1.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null' because it contains an object field at offset 0 that is incorrectly aligned or overlapped by a non-object field. 
(I am only listing one, as the others are all the same just different names)

I'm not very good with explicit struct layouts, so I'm not sure how to fix the problem, perhaps someone here knows?  Obviously removing them worked just fine since I'm in the DirectX build so I don't actually need MojoShader.

I am mildly concerned though, as http://www.codeproject.com/Articles/66243/Marshaling-with-C-Chapter-3-Marshaling-Compound-Ty
mentions:

As a result, we cannot union both members of our example, because whether marshaling the second variable charArray as an array, a System.String, or as a System.Text.StringBuilder, it is still a reference-type. Therefore, we have to leave the benefits of unions and marshal only a single member. For our example, we will create two marshaling types for our union, one with the first member marshaled, and the other with the other member.

Changing the public string types to IntPtrs works for loading, but it will require marshaling the string manually.

Is there any chance of getting a version of the TwoMGFX functions that operate in memory rather than having to work with files? Something that takes shader code and gives back byte code?

Right now I have to basically invoke the program as if was run as an exe:

``` c#
 public static Effect LoadShader(GraphicsDevice device, string filePath)
        {
            string outputPath = filePath + ".mgfxo";
            TwoMGFX.Program.Main(new string[] {filePath, outputPath, "/DX11"});
            byte[] byteCode = File.ReadAllBytes(outputPath);
            File.Delete(outputPath);
            return new Effect(device, byteCode);
        }
```

It would be nice to be able to just get the byte code:

If you create a render target and put it on screen, it's shows upside down!

Sample:

renderTarget = new RenderTarget2D(...
device.SetRenderTarget(renderTarget);
// draw stuff
graphicsdevice.SetRenderTarget(null);
myTexture = (Texture2D)renderTarget;
spritebatch.Draw(myTexture..

Something with the transformation matrix, perhaps?

My shader has:

``` c
        #ifdef MGFX
            VertexShader = compile vs_4_0_level_9_1  VertexProgram();
            PixelShader  = compile ps_4_0_level_9_1  PixelProgram();
        #else 
```

but when I compile, it thinks its 2.0!

``` c#
Shaders\\Standard\\img_orennayar.fx(135,23): error X5608: Compiled shader code uses too many arithmetic instruction slots (83). Max. allowed by the target (ps_2_0) is 64.
```

I am loading this at runtime via:

``` C#
            string outputPath = filePath + ".mgfxo";
            TwoMGFX.Program.Main(new string[] {filePath, outputPath, "/DX11"});
            byte[] byteCode = File.ReadAllBytes(outputPath);
            File.Delete(outputPath);
            return new Effect(device, byteCode);
```

I'm testing out having multiple sub windows each with their own GraphicsDevice.  I was able to locate a bunch of places where monogame isn't multi-device friendly, static cache in Effect, Sampler States, RenderStates ( Blend, Raster, etc).  I've managed to get around all of them, but now I seem to crash on one I can't figure out. Does anyone know what could cause this to crash:

``` C#
//In TextureCollection.cs

#elif DIRECTX
                if (_textures[i] == null || _textures[i].IsDisposed)
                    pixelShaderStage.SetShaderResource(i, null);
                else
                    //HERE
                    pixelShaderStage.SetShaderResource(i, _textures[i].GetShaderResourceView());
```

It seems to me like the texture is loaded from the previous device context, but I was able to see it for one frame before it crashed.

Any ideas?

Also, would my multi-device rendering changes be useful to check in? As it stands, without them the Debug.Assertions just fail.
